            <h3>Sushi Wakon</h3>
            <p>This Michelin star sushi stop boasts a menu that changes everyday depending on what produce looks freshest at the fish market. Opt for the omakase menu (a type of meal consisting of dishes selected by the chef)… but be sure to book ahead, the pint-sized eatery only seats 10 people!</p>
            <h3>Jan Jan Yokocho alley</h3>
            <p>After a few minutes wandering through Jan Jan Yokocho alley, you’ll realise why Osaka has a reputation for being one of the best cities for eating. Here the kushikatsu (sizzling meat skewers) cost just over $1 and come with a side of all you can eat cabbage.</p>
            <h3>Hariju Dontonbori</h3>
            <p>Sample some amazing Kobe beef at this legendary Osakan restaurant, which has been serving up soul warming hot pots and sukiyaki for over 100 years. The set meals cost between $80 - $200 depending on the choice of beef, which is available in five grades.</p>
            <h3>Hajime</h3>
            <p>This experimental eatery, named after owner Hajime Yoneda was this year awarded three Michelin stars. The inventive menu is inspired by themes of earth and space, and dishes are almost too beautiful to eat… almost. For those lucky few who can get a table, it’s an unforgettable dining experience.</p>
            <h3>Yoshino Sushi</h3>
            <p>Founded in 1841, Yoshino Sushi has been around long enough to have earned a reputation for serving up serious sushi. Settle in for some oshi-zushi a type of pressed sushi which originated in Osaka, or enjoy a lunch box packed with favourites like vinegar treated mackerel and eel.</p>
          </div>
