          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <h3>Okonomiyaki</h3>
              <p>This signature and original Osakan dish derives its name from “okonomi” meaning, “what you like” and they’re not kidding, this savory pancake-like dish is a sort of choose your own adventure food experience where you can pick the flavours and a chef cooks it before your eyes. The flavour choices vary across Japan, but in Osaka the flour based batter is mixed with octopus or prawns, egg and shredded cabbage, then ladled onto a hot grill and served hot topped with sizzling pork belly, dried bonito and mayonnaise.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="images/kushikatsu.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <h3>Kushikatsu</h3>
              <p>The bite size skewers of deep fried meat and vegetables were invented in Shinsekai, a district in southern Osaka, which remains the best place to sample this traditional street food. The skewers come in a number different flavours including offal and cartilage for the more adventurous. Most eateries offer a communal sweet tangy sauce but be sure to only dip your skewer once! It’s considered very rude to double dip.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="images/takoyaki.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <h3>Takoyaki (also known as “octopus balls”)</h3>
              <p>Takoyaki literally means “grilled octopus” and is a crowd favourite amongst Osakans. Street vendors combine the gloopy egg based batter with roughly cut slices of fresh octopus, pickled ginger and green onions and then spoon the mix into a special takoyaki pan which forms the batter into delectable sizzling spheres. Once cooked, the balls are drizzled with sweet takoyaki sauce and mayonnaise.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="images/yakiniku.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <h3>Yakiniku</h3>
              <p>Any connoisseur of meat knows Kobe beef is king. This special type of Japanese wagyu is one of the world’s best and comes from Kobe, a region located just 30 minutes by train from Osaka, which means it’s readily available. One of the best ways to enjoy Kobe beef is by Yakiniku, which is the Japanese style of cooking meat yourself on a charcoal grill in the middle of your table. The fat marbled mouth watering slices only need a few seconds on the grill and are so packed with flavours they don’t need any accompaniments.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="c-carousel__item">
          <div class="c-carousel__cover">
            <img class="c-carousel__image" src="images/fugu-sashimi.jpg" alt="">
          </div>
          <div class="c-carousel__caption">
            <div class="s-entry-content">
              <h3>Tessa</h3>
              <p>Osaka’s famous sashimi made from poisonous fugu, or globefish. It takes two years for chefs to earn the certification to be allowed to prepare the dangerous fish, which is designed to retain just enough poison to numb your lips! Although the dish is heavily regulated, be careful... the problematic puffer fish accounts for the majority of Japan’s food poisoning deaths, and results in around 40 hospitalisations a year!</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
